  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several significant legal precedents in money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major case establishing bank reporting requirements\n- Imposed significant penalties for failure to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) cases\n- Established framework for financial institution reporting and compliance\n- Created mandatory suspicious activity reporting standards\n\n3. United States v. HSBC (2012)\n- Large settlement for inadequate anti-money laundering controls\n- Highlighted international banking compliance requirements\n\n4. Several Supreme Court decisions have refined money laundering statutes, establishing:\n- Broader interpretations of financial transaction definitions\n- Clearer standards for proving intent\n- Guidelines for prosecuting complex financial crimes\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of these legal precedents? I can discuss their details while maintaining an objective, factual approach.",
